f [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">That’s according to the US Customs and Border Protection’s (CBP) recently-published January 12th ruling that approved <a href="/2024/1/17/24042395/apple-watch-ultra-2-series-9-ban-blood-oxygen-stores">Apple’s modification</a> meant to lift the <a href="/24009254/apple-watch-itc-ban-patent-dispute">Apple Watch ban</a>. </p><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup mt-12 font-fkroman text-gray-33 dark:text-gray-ef [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">CBP chief Dax Terrill wrote that Masimo installed “otherwise restricted software that, but for the jailbreaking, would not have been feasible.” He concluded that the software change “would appear to resolve the issue of infringement.”</p><br/></div><div class="pt-12"><div class="relative z-10 font-polysans leading-120"><a class="text-16 leading-120 text-gray-4a shadow-underline-blurple hover:text-blurple dark:text-gray-ef dark:shadow-underline-franklin dark:hover:text-franklin" href="https://rulings.cbp.gov/ruling/H335304" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">CROSS Customs Rulings Online Search System</a><p class="mt-8 text-12 font-bold uppercase tracking-15 text-gray-63 dark:text-gray-bd">[<!-- -->rulings.cbp.gov<!-- -->]</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></li><li role="article" class="mx-[-16px] mb-40 mt-[-40px] px-16 last:mb-0 md:mx-0 md:px-0" id="stream-entry-dbd967c8-e344-4e0f-bcc1-45981f7bd492"><div class="border-solid border-blurple-df pt-40 sm:border-b-0 border-b"><div class="mb-40"><div class="duet--content-cards--content-card z-10 flex max-w-container-md flex-row border-b border-solid border-gray-cc px-0 last-of-t