><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline font-fkroman text-gray-33 dark:text-gray-ef [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">If you got a Series 9 or Ultra 2 before Apple had to <a href="/2024/1/17/24042395/apple-watch-ultra-2-series-9-ban-blood-oxygen-stores">remove the blood oxygen feature</a> from new ones on January 17th, congrats! </p><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup mt-12 font-fkroman text-gray-33 dark:text-gray-ef [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">But if you break your watch doing parkour and replace it with AppleCare, will you lose the feature? That’s a “definite maybe,” according to <em>Bloomberg’</em>s<em> </em>Mark Gurman. He<em> </em>wrote today<em> </em>in the subscriber version of <em>Power On</em> that Apple has told AppleCare reps that replacements might not have it.</p><br/></div></div></div></div></div></li><li role="article" class="mx-[-16px] mb-40 mt-[-40px] px-16 last:mb-0 md:mx-0 md:px-0" id="stream-entry-809e51b9-e06a-4a15-92e9-c4826c14a1ef"><div class="border-solid border-blurple-df pt-40 sm:border-b-0 border-b"><div class="mb-40"><div class="duet--content-cards--content-card z-10 flex max-w-container-md flex-row border-b border-solid border-gray-cc px-0 last-of-type:border-b-0 dark:border-gray-31"><div class="flex min-w-0 flex-1 flex-col"><div class="mb-10 flex items-center"><div class="absolute left-[-2px] hidden h-6 w-12 border-y-2 border-white bg-[#DFCFFF] md:block"></div><div class="relative mr-8 block h-[36px] w-[36px] flex-none overflow-hidden rounded-full border border-solid border-gray-ef bg-[#DFCFFF]"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidde