 font-bold">Jan 18</p><p><span><a class="hover:shadow-underline-blurple" href="/authors/jay-peters">Jay Peters</a></span></p></div></div><div class="font-polysans text-black dark:text-gray-ef leading-150"><div class="inline pr-4 text-17 font-bold md:text-17">“Apple Watch Series 9 and Ultra 2 no longer include the blood oxygen feature.”</div><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline font-fkroman text-gray-33 dark:text-gray-ef [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">Following <a href="/2024/1/17/24042395/apple-watch-ultra-2-series-9-ban-blood-oxygen-stores">yesterday’s news</a>, that’s the text now shown at the top of Apple’s <a href="https://www.apple.com/apple-watch-series-9/">Series 9</a> and <a href="https://www.apple.com/apple-watch-ultra-2/">Ultra 2</a> websites.</p><br/></div><div class="pt-12"><div class="flex max-w-[500px] flex-row flex-wrap"><div class="w-full rounded-[3px] border border-solid border-gray-cc dark:border-gray-31"><div class="transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out"><div class="fixed inset-0 h-[110vh] w-full bg-white transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out z-[-1] cursor-default opacity-0" role="button" aria-label="Close" tabindex="0"></div><div role="button" aria-label="Zoom" tabindex="0" class="visible z-30 w-full origin-center transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out cursor-zoom-in"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:relative"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;padding-top:89.54248366013073%"></span><img alt="A screenshot of the Apple Watch Ultra 2 website. A banner at the top says “Apple&amp;nbsp;Watch Series&amp;nbsp;9 and Ultra&amp;nbsp;2 no lon