-franklin">My colleague Emma Roth recently wrote about how the company’s patent fight with True Wearables helps explain <a href="/2023/12/28/24016913/apple-patent-dispute-masimo-lagemo-true-wearables">Masimo’s confidence</a> in its <a href="/24009254/apple-watch-itc-ban-patent-dispute">Apple Watch fight</a>. </p><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup mt-12 font-fkroman text-gray-33 dark:text-gray-ef [&amp;_a]:relative [&amp;_a]:z-10   [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin [&amp;_a]:text-gray-33 [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-gray-33 dark:[&amp;_a]:text-gray-ef dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-franklin">In a profile of Joe Kiani today, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/tech/joe-kiani-entrepreneur-apple-warning-52eb09a9?mod=followamazon"><em>The Wall Street Journal</em> writes</a> about still more examples. One 2016 win gave Masimo a $300 million dollar payout from Philips and a deal that “ended up generating more than $1 billion” for the company. Before that, Masimo won “nearly $800 million” in “damages and royalties” from Nellcor.</p><br/></div><div class="pt-12"><div class="relative z-10 font-polysans leading-120"><a class="text-16 leading-120 text-gray-4a shadow-underline-blurple hover:text-blurple dark:text-gray-ef dark:shadow-underline-franklin dark:hover:text-franklin" href="https://www.wsj.com/tech/joe-kiani-entrepreneur-apple-warning-52eb09a9?mod=followamazon" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">The Entrepreneur Who Bet His Company on a Fight With Apple</a><p class="mt-8 text-12 font-bold uppercase tracking-15 text-gray-63 dark:text-gray-bd">[<!-- -->WSJ<!-- -->]</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></li><li role="article" class="mx-[-16px] mb-40 mt-[-40px] px-16 last:mb-0 md:mx-0 md:px-0" id="stream-entry-11ee69d6-2d1b-4846-ac6c-750298476919"><div class="border-solid border-blurple-df pt-40 sm:border-b-0 border-b"><div class="mb-40"><div><div class="mb-10 flex items-center"><div class="absolute left-[-2px] hidden h-6 w-12 border-y-2 b