1]\n","originalPublishDate":"2024-01-05T14:54:05.590Z","publishDate":"2024-01-05T14:54:05.590Z","url":"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/5/24026522/why-the-itc-denied-staying-the-apple-watch-ban"},{"title":"Masimo kept winning on the way to its Apple Watch fight.","seoDescription":null,"dek":null,"author":{"fullName":"Wes Davis","authorProfile":{"url":"https://www.theverge.com/authors/wes-davis"}},"contributors":[],"seoArticleBody":"My colleague Emma Roth recently wrote about how the company’s patent fight with True Wearables helps explain Masimo’s confidence in its Apple Watch fight. \n\nIn a profile of Joe Kiani today, The Wall Street Journal writes about still more examples. One 2016 win gave Masimo a $300 million dollar payout from Philips and a deal that “ended up generating more than $1 billion” for the company. Before that, Masimo won “nearly $800 million” in “damages and royalties” from Nellcor.\n\n[Attachment: https://www.wsj.com/tech/joe-kiani-entrepreneur-apple-warning-52eb09a9?mod=followamazon]\n","originalPublishDate":"2023-12-30T20:25:01.806Z","publishDate":"2023-12-30T20:25:01.806Z","url":"https://www.theverge.com/2023/12/30/24019995/masimo-kept-winning-on-the-way-to-its-apple-watch-fight"},{"title":"Why Masimo thought it could take on Apple","seoDescription":{"plaintext":"Apple’s legal battle with medical device maker Masimo started when the company hired Marcelo Lamego, a former Masimo employee privy to confidential information."},"dek":{"plaintext":"Before it sued Apple, medical device maker Masimo filed a lawsuit against a startup on similar grounds — and won."},"author":{"fullName":"Emma Roth","authorProfile":{"url":"https://www.theverge.com/authors/emma-roth"}},"contributors":[],"seoArticleBody":"For over three years now, Apple has been entrenched in a messy legal battle over a single feature on the Apple Watch — and Apple’s opponent, medical device maker Masimo, seems confident it can win. And there’s a good reason Masimo might believe that: the 